    <statement><p>Simplify the following expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain on the simplified expression.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{-r^{2}+r}{-3+4r-r^{2}}}=}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{r}{r-3}, r\ne 1</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simplify the expression, we first factor both the numerator and denominator, and then cross out common factors.</p>
<p>If a polynomial is not in order, we order it by the variable<rsq/>s degrees.</p>
<p>If the leading coefficient is negative, we factor out <m>-1</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{-r^{2}+r}{-3+4r-r^{2}}} \amp = \frac{{-\left(r^{2}-r\right)}}{{-r^{2}+4r-3}} \\
                     \amp = \frac{{-r\mathopen{}\left(r-1\right)}}{{-\left(r^{2}-4r+3\right)}} \\
                     \amp = \frac{{-r\mathopen{}\left(r-1\right)}}{{-\left(r-1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}} \\
                     \amp = {\frac{r}{r-3}, r\ne 1}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>r - 1</m> was crossed out, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>r \ne 1</m>.</p>
</solution>
